Simple Phenomena of Magnetism

1. Magnetism: The Basics

Forces between Magnetic Poles

  • The ends of a magnet are called poles.
  • Magnets have two poles: a north pole and a south pole.
  • Magnetic forces are strongest at the poles.
  • When two magnets are held close together, a force exists between them:
    • Like poles repel (push apart). For example, North repels North.
    • Opposite poles attract (pull together). For example, North attracts South.
  • The attraction or repulsion between poles is an example of a non-contact force.
  • (Please refer to the diagrams in your notes showing magnet attraction and repulsion).

Uses of Magnets

Type Examples
Permanent Magnets Compasses, fridge magnets, holding cabinet doors shut.
Electromagnets Cranes for lifting cars, circuit breakers, electric bells.

2. Types of Magnets

Magnetic Materials

  • Magnetic materials experience a force when placed in a magnetic field.
  • Examples include: iron, steel, nickel, and cobalt.
  • Steel is an alloy made from iron.

Permanent vs. Temporary Magnets

  • Permanent magnets are made from 'hard' magnetic materials (like steel) and produce their own magnetic field. They retain their magnetism.
  • Temporary magnets (or induced magnets) are made from 'soft' magnetic materials (like iron). They become magnets when placed in a magnetic field, but lose their magnetism quickly when the field is removed.
  • Induced magnetism is the process where a magnetic material becomes a magnet when it is brought near to a magnet. The end of the material closer to the magnet gets the opposite pole, creating a force of attraction.

3. Magnetic Fields

Defining a Magnetic Field

  • A magnetic field is a region around a magnet where a force acts on another magnet or on a magnetic material.

Magnetic Field Lines

  • Magnetic fields are represented by magnetic field lines.
  • These lines show the strength and direction of the field.
  • The direction of the field line is the direction the force would be on a 'north pole' placed at that point.
  • By convention, field lines always point from north to south.
  • The spacing of the lines indicates the field's strength: closer lines mean a stronger field.
  • The magnetic field is strongest at the poles, which is where the field lines are most concentrated.
  • (Please refer to the diagrams in your notes showing the field lines for a single bar magnet, and for attracting and repelling poles).

4. Plotting Magnetic Fields

Method 1: Using Iron Filings

  1. Place the magnet on a flat surface with a piece of paper on top.
  2. Gently sprinkle iron filings over the paper.
  3. Carefully tap the paper. The iron filings will align themselves with the magnetic field lines, revealing the shape of the field.

Method 2: Using Plotting Compasses

  1. Place the magnet on a piece of paper.
  2. Draw a dot near one pole of the magnet.
  3. Place a plotting compass next to the dot. The compass needle will point along the field line.
  4. Use a pencil to mark a new dot at the tip of the compass needle.
  5. Move the compass so its base is at the new dot. Repeat the process.
  6. Continue this chain of dots from one pole to the other.
  7. Connect the dots with a smooth curve to draw one magnetic field line. The arrow should point from North to South.
  8. Repeat the process starting from different points to map out the entire field.
  9. (Please refer to the diagram in your notes showing how to use a compass to plot field lines).
